				 TCS inks pact with Dutch firm
 OUR CORRESPONDENT			TCS managing director S. Ramadorai (right) with chief operating officer N. Chandrasekaran in Mumbai on Thursday. (Fotocorp)		Mumbai, Oct. 18: Tata Consultancy Services (TCS) today signed a $1.2-billion deal with consumer and media information services firm Nielsen Company of the Netherlands.																								This is the biggest deal in Indias software industry.This is a pure services deal and does not include the acquisition of any assets or any other component, TCS officials said.																								We have entered into a strategic partnership with Nielsen Company where we will bring in all the competencies of TCS to deliver IT services, S. Ramadorai, CEO and managing director of TCS, said here today. 																								TCS will provide the service to Nielsen through its network delivery model. It will be responsible for important IT and operational processes and help Nielsen integrate multiple systems, technologies and processes on a global scale. 																								TCS has not made any upfront payment for the deal and officials say the $1.2-billion revenue is fixed. IT companies sometimes pay a guarantee amount that they stand to forfeit if their services dont measure up to the stated claims.																								The deal consists of multiple components, said S. Mahalingam, chief financial officer of TCS.																								It consists of a full IT application service, a few range of BPO services, work planning and billing. It also includes a knowledge process outsourcing component which will have analysis, reporting and reference of data management and strategic transformation engagement from ERP to a SAP-based platform, he added. 																								Following the deal, TCS will ramp up its IT and BPO segments. Company officials, however, did not give any numbers. 																								The revenues from the deal will be reflected in the third-quarter numbers of this fiscal, Mahalingam said. 																								Refusing to give out any details of price margins, Mahalingam said the overall margin of the deal had taken into consideration an inflationary component. The pricing is different for different services that we will provide. The pricing will protect our margins, Mahalingam said. 																								As part of the agreement, TCS will take direct responsibility of a Nielsen team in Vadodara, Gujarat. 																								The Vadodara team specialises in information management relating to Nielsens retail measurement service, a core product of the company for packaged goods manufacturers and retailers. 																								The TCS stock surged 5 per cent to Rs 1,149.50  its highest level in more than nine weeks  after the deal was announced. It closed at Rs 1,111, up 1.45 per cent. 
